{
  "text": "Saponins have been shown to have both positive and negative effects on the viability of human sperm cells in vitro with some ginseng saponins increasing motility as well as progression of sperm [CITATION_1] while Sesbania sesban saponins were spermicidal at 1·0 -1·3 mg/ml [CITATION_2] . It is debatable how relevant these in vitro effects are for dietary saponins as there are relatively few reports in this regard.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "30620136",
    "[CITATION_2]": "38727020"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "38727020": {
      "title": "Molluscicidal saponins from Sesbania sesban",
      "abstract": "The phytochemical investigation of the aerial parts of Sesbania sesban Merrill (Leguminosae) afforded three glucuronide derivatives of oleanolic acid. Among them, saponin 1, identified as 3-O-[α-L-rhamnopyranosyl-(1→3)-β-D-glucuronopyranosyl]-oleanolic acid, was responsible for the molluscicidal activity of the plant."
    },
    "30620136": {
      "title": "Effect of Panax notoginseng saponins on sperm motility and progression in vitro",
      "abstract": "Summary In this present study we investigated the effects of a saponin fraction prepared from the roots of Panax notoginseng (Burt.) F. H. Chen (Family Araliaceae), on human sperm motility and progression in vitro . Fifteeen human semen samples were collected and qualified according to the criteria of W.H.O. The saponin fraction was evaluated at 1.0 mg/ml and 2.0 mg/ml respectively. The results demonstrate that the fraction increased motility as well as progression of sperm at the 60 th minute or the 120 th minute."
    }
  }
}